04815nam a22006135i 9780773557598DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192019xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735575987 a10.1515/97807735575982doi  a(DE-B1597)656508  a(OCoLC)1083217491  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBQ749.O585bT67 2019 7aREL0070202bisacsh04a294.309713/5412231 aBarua, D. Mitra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSeeding Buddhism with Multiculturalism :bThe Transmission of Sri Lankan Buddhism in Toronto /cD. Mitra Barua. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b6 b&w images, 6 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAdvancing Studies in Religion ;v600tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Studying the Intercultural and Intergenerational Transmission of Buddhism -- tCommunity Formation of Sri Lankan Buddhists in Toronto -- tDhamma Education and the Historical Construction of Buddhist Identities -- tAn Inclusive and Harmonious Buddhism: A Buddhist Response to Multiculturalism in Canada -- tThe Intergenerational and Intercultural Negotiation of Buddhism -- tGrowing up as Sri Lankan Canadian Buddhists in Toronto -- tConclusion: Making Sense of Reconfigured Buddhism in Toronto -- tFirst-Generation Buddhists -- tSecond-Generation Buddhists -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aImmigrants often face considerable challenges when it comes to preserving their cultural and religious teachings. D. Mitra Barua argues that the Sri Lankan Buddhist community in Toronto has maintained its coherence and integrity not despite but because of the need for cultural adaptations. Drawing on survey data, over fifty in-depth interviews with temple monks, educators, parents, and children, and fieldwork conducted in Toronto and Colombo, Sri Lanka, Seeding Buddhism with Multiculturalism examines how a religious tradition is transmitted from one generation to the next in a new cultural setting, and what happens during that process of transmission. Barua demonstrates that Buddhists have passed on Buddhist beliefs, attitudes, and practices to their Canadian-born youth, who in turn have constructed their own distinct Buddhist identity, influenced by the individualistic, egalitarian, and secular cultural ambience in Toronto. Through creative fieldwork and translocal analysis – taking into account migrants' geographical, cultural, and familial ties to multiple locales – this book further explains that pre-migration experiences often shape and determine the success or failure of intergenerational transmission. An ethnographic religious study with an uncommon depth of perspective, Seeding Buddhism with Multiculturalism shows that first- and second-generation Sri Lankan Buddhists in Toronto are successfully practising Theravāda Buddhism within a Canadian context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBuddhismzOntariozToronto. 0aBuddhismzSri LankazColombo. 0aBuddhistszOntariozToronto. 0aImmigrantszOntariozToronto. 0aIntergenerational communicationzOntariozToronto. 0aMulticulturalismxReligious aspectsxBuddhism. 0aSri LankanszOntariozTorontoxEthnic identity. 0aSri LankanszOntariozTorontoxReligion. 7aRELIGION / Buddhism / Rituals & Practice.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311127268908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2019z978311127498040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355759840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773557598423Coveru